        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose a spectral scanning program of a close pair of galaxies at z~7.4.  In the scientific justification, we described how we derived the predicted [CII] flux densities for these sources
of 1.32 and 0.71 mJy, respectively.  We base our requested integration time by requiring a 4-sigma significance detection of the fainter of these two lines, for a desired sensitivity per
 pointing of 0.1775 mJy.  The brighter line will be detected at 9-sigma.  We note that in the conservative case of using the observed (non-dust-corrected) UV SFR to estimate the [CII] flux, 
we will still obtain a 3.3-sigma detection of the fainter of the two lines.

We request an angular resolution of 0.4".  This is about half of the separation between the two sources (~0.9"), thus we will be able to distinguish the two [CII] lines (additionally, while
they are likely physically associated, the redshifts are likely not identical, so the lines will be offset in frequency space as well).  The individual galaxies have diameters of ~0.2-0.25"
in HST imaging, so they will remain unresolved, thus we assume a point source for the time calculation.  Both sources will be at the center of the field of view, so there will be no power
loss (specifically, the coordinates entered in the OT is the position between the two sources; the coordinates of each galaxy individually is given in Table 1).  To derive our desired 
integration time, we assume that we will average over a velocity of 150 km/s (assumed to be the line width of these sources).  
The total integration time for one observation with these 
parameters is 33.25 minutes (without overheads).

As our primary goal is to measure the redshift of this pair of galaxies, we require a spectral scan.  A scan of five frequency settings from 213 - 247.75 GHz covers 99.3% of the integral
of the redshift probability distribution function - this is key, as even if we do not detect the line, we will know at high likelihood that we observed the wavelength of its [CII] emission,
and thus can still derive a useful (and publishable) upper limit.  Figure 3 shows our scan tunings alongside the redshift likelihood for these sources.  
We use the 1.875 GHz bandwidth, as we do not require higher spectral resolution, and we wish the maximize the frequencies covered.

We will use the system-defined calibrations.  The total requested time, including all five observations along with associated overheads and calibrations is 9.2 hr.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
