    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose for 9.2 hr of Band 6 spectroscopy to confirm the redshifts of a close pair of galaxies which have a photometric redshift of z ~ 7.4, robustly placing them deep in the epoch of reionization. While Lyman-alpha has long been the spectroscopic redshift tracer of choice, deep observations with state-of-the-art instruments on 10m telescopes show that this line is not detectable for the vast majority of z &gt; 7 galaxies, possibly due to scattering by neutral gas in the intergalactic medium. Lacking Lyman-alpha, the [CII] 158 μm line is the best alternative, and it is now detectable with the advent of ALMA.  Each of this close pair of galaxies is bright (for z ~ 7), and has a high star-formation rate, implying that [CII] can be detected efficiently.  A spectral scan of most of Band 6 will cover 99.3% of the photometric redshift probability distribution function.  If detected, these galaxies will be among the most distant spectroscopically confirmed galaxies.  If not detected, we will place strong constraints on the evolution of the [CII]-SFR relation.  These observations will be the first step of a future ALMA program to confirm the redshifts for a large sample of z &gt; 7 galaxies.</prp:abstract>
